{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"318578b0-3c9e-40c8-813e-4cb7ad13ee35","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect the trace (30s example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** in Visual Studio, PerfView, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app) (use `--format speedscope` for the latter).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (distroless image), use **`dotnet-monitor`** as a sidecar instead.\n- For production, prefer `--duration` over manual stop to avoid forgetting a running trace.\n- `createdump` or `dotnet-dump` won't help here — those are for memory/crash analysis, not CPU.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7000b80e-e06e-4547-8897-fdc467c231a8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostics/troubleshooting question - I can answer from knowledge without needing tools.","outputTokens":381,"requestId":"6811:23D333:A8D658B:B7DD356:69FD3C81"},"id":"42af67d6-daed-4c64-8ded-6bc0e4f597a3","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:29:46.954Z","parentId":"7ff7d539-5c53-49d2-bae9-139bdf24cb2a"}
